2 Network basics –reminder

“clusternetwork2012.csv” is the adjacency matrix of a knowledge sharing network in an industry cluster. Nodes are firms, edges represent asking for technical advice.

# network from adjacency matrix
Knet <- graph.adjacency(as.matrix(read.csv("clusternetwork2012.csv", sep = ";",
                                           header = TRUE, row.names = 1)))

# degree distr plot
hist(degree(Knet), col = "darkgreen", main = "Degree distribution plot")

Plot the network

set.seed(10) # for reproduction
layout1 <- layout_with_graphopt(Knet, niter=800, charge=0.2)# set up the layout

     vertex.color="lightgray", edge.color="black",
     vertex.size=25, edge.arrow.size=0.4)

Construct a dataframe for node indicators

3 Network measures

Calculate a few basic network measures and check for correlations

  1. local clustering
# lc - local clustering
lc <- transitivity(Knet, type="local")
lc
##  [1] 0.4848485 0.3454545 0.2000000 0.3626374 0.3636364 0.4044118 0.5000000
##  [8] 0.5090909 0.2571429 0.3272727 0.1847291 0.3904762 0.1976285 0.2338462
## [15] 0.2549020 0.1801802 0.2400000 0.3333333 0.2761905 0.5416667 0.3333333
## [22] 0.2435897 0.4358974 0.8333333 0.2086022 0.2010582
  1. brokerage
# brokerage based on Burt's constraint measure
brokerage <- constraint(Knet)
brokerage
##        P1        P2        P3        P4        P5        P6        P7 
## 0.2457402 0.2356001 0.2822209 0.2073183 0.2560348 0.2023608 0.4768874 
##        P8        P9       P10       P11       P12       P13       P15 
## 0.2113500 0.2503627 0.2795187 0.1846781 0.2263966 0.1947030 0.1849786 
##       P16       P17       P18       P19       P20       P21       P22 
## 0.2105769 0.1650281 0.1948308 0.2079876 0.1883871 0.1946837 0.2225496 
##       P23       P24       P25       P26       P30 
## 0.2353624 0.2152239 0.3546452 0.1781866 0.1864156
# check the distribution of constraint based brokerage
hist(lc, col="darkblue", main='', xlab='Local clustering', xlim=c(0,1))

Add local clustering and brokerage to the dataframe

df <- cbind(df, lc, brokerage)

Visualize the constraint based brokers!

# create a color column based on above median brokerage
df$broker_col <- "lightgray"
df$broker_col[which(df$brokerage > median(df$brokerage))] <- "darkblue"


set.seed(10) # for reproduction
layout1 <- layout_with_graphopt(Knet, niter=800, charge=0.2) # set up the layout

plot(Knet, layout=layout1,
     vertex.color=df$broker_col, edge.color="black",
     vertex.size=25, edge.arrow.size=0.4)

How do degree, brokerage and local clustering correlate? What does it mean? What is the general reason behind it (from a network structure point of view)?

# simple correlations
cor(df$degree, df$brokerage) 
## [1] -0.730879
cor(df$degree, df$lc)
## [1] -0.6892955
cor(df$brokerage, df$lc)
## [1] 0.5328967

5 Create random graphs

There are many possibilities to create random graphs.

Random graphs according to the Erdos-Renyi model (see lectures)
n - number of nodes
p - edge probability

set.seed(10) # run together with the function for reproduction
ernet <- erdos.renyi.game(n = 100, p.or.m = 350, type = 'gnm')

Generate random networks by the Watts-Strogatz small-world model (see lecture)
dim - dimension of the starting set
size - number of nodes
nei - number of neighbors a node should be connected
p - rewiring probability

set.seed(10)
wsnet <- sample_smallworld(dim = 1, size = 100, nei = 3, p = 0.1)

Two basic properties of small-world networks are high clustering and low average path length.

# clustering
transitivity(wsnet, type='global')
## [1] 0.3226633
# average path length
mean_distance(wsnet)
## [1] 3.169091

7 Dynamic network (intro)

Networks (mostly) change over time! ’filmdata9806.csv contains anonymized data on Hungarian feature films, their year of production and their creators. Let’s construct networks of movie creators and see how the network changes over time!

First, check the data!

# import the dataset
film_df <- data.frame(read.csv("filmdata9806.csv", sep = ";", header = TRUE))
head(film_df)

# filter data for 1998 only
data1998 <- subset(film_df, year==1998)

# create an n x n matrix = adjacency matrix

# set the diagonal to 0

GREAT! But we need one for every year.. Write a loop that constructs a network for each year.

graphs <- list() # store graphs in a list
years <- c(1998:2006) # iterator

for(i in 1:length(years)){
  dt <- subset(film_df, year==years[i]) # filter data by time
  mat <- table(dt$creator_id, dt$film_id)
  mat <- mat %*% t(mat)
  diag(mat) <- 0
  graphs[[i]] <- graph.adjacency(mat, mode='undirected')
}

# add names to list elements
names(graphs) <- paste0("graph", c(1998:2006))

How the number of nodes and edges changed over time?

# loop to collect data on nodes and edges
nodes <- c() # vector to store no. nodes
edges <- c() # vector to store no. edges
years <- c(1998:2006) # iterator

for(i in 1:length(years)){
  nodes[i] <- vcount(graphs[[i]])
  edges[i] <- ecount(graphs[[i]])
}

# dataframe
networks_df <- data.frame(years, nodes, edges)

# set up barplots
par(mfrow=c(1,2)) # 2 barplots next to each other

barplot(networks_df$nodes, names.arg = years, main="Number of nodes 1998-2006")
barplot(networks_df$edges, names.arg = years, main="Number of nodes 1998-2006")

Woah - there was a huge drop in the number of movie creators around 2003! Are these actually well-connected graphs?

Well - they are clearly NOT well connected. In 2003 the largest component consist of 27 nodes ONLY.
TRICK - add a time dimension/decay to ties. Let’s assume that creators are connected for 3 years after collaborating on a movie.
Let’s reconstruct networks this way and see how they changed!

graphs <- list() # store graphs in a list
years <- c(2000:2006) # iterator

for(i in 1:length(years)){
  dt <- subset(film_df, year>=(years[i]-2) & year<=years[i])
  mat <- table(dt$creator_id, dt$film_id)
  mat <- mat %*% t(mat)
  diag(mat) <- 0
  graphs[[i]] <- graph.adjacency(mat, mode='undirected')
}

# add names to list elements
names(graphs) <- paste0("graph", c(2000:2006))


# loop to collect data on nodes and edges
nodes <- c()
edges <- c()

for(i in 1:length(years)){
  nodes[i] <- vcount(graphs[[i]])
  edges[i] <- ecount(graphs[[i]])
}

networks_df <- data.frame(years, nodes, edges)

# set up barplots
par(mfrow=c(1,2)) # 2 barplots next to each other

barplot(networks_df$nodes, names.arg = years, main="Number of nodes 2000-2006")
barplot(networks_df$edges, names.arg = years, main="Number of nodes 2000-2006")
